javaslang.control

Interface Try<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - Value type in the case of success.
    All Superinterfaces:
    CheckedFunctor<T>, CheckedMonad<T,Try<?>>, HigherKinded<T,Try<?>>, Iterable<T>, Serializable, ValueObject
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    Failure, Success

    public interface Try<T>
extends CheckedMonad<T,Try<?>>, ValueObject, Iterable<T>
    An implementation similar to Scala's Try control.

      • flatten

        default <U> Try<U> flatten()
        Flattens a Try, assuming that the elements are of type Try<U>

        Examples: 

         
 new Success<>(1).flatten();                                  // throws
 new Success<>(new Success<>(1)).flatten();             // = Success (1)
 new Success<>(new Failure<>(new Error(""))).flatten(); // = Failure("Error")
 new Failure<>(new Error("")).flatten();                      // = Failure("Error")
        Specified by:
        flatten in interface CheckedMonad<T,Try<?>>
        Type Parameters:
        U - component type of the result Try
        Returns:
        a new Try

      • flatten

        default <U,TRY extends HigherKinded<U,Try<?>>> Try<U> flatten(Try.CheckedFunction<? super T,? extends TRY> f)
        Flattens a nested, monadic structure using a function.

        Examples: 

         
 Match<Try<U>> f
    .caze((Try<U> o) -> o)
    .caze((U u) -> new Success<>(u))
    .build();
 new Success<>(1).flatten();                                  // = Success(1)
 new Success<>(new Success<>(1)).flatten(f);            // = Success(1)
 new Success<>(new Failure<>(new Error(""))).flatten(); // = Failure("Error")
 new Failure<>(new Error("")).flatten();                      // = Failure("Error")
        Specified by:
        flatten in interface CheckedMonad<T,Try<?>>
        Type Parameters:
        U - component type of the result Try
        TRY - a Try&lt;U&gt;
        Parameters:
        f - a function which maps elements of this Try to Trys
        Returns:
        a new Try

      • andThen

        default Try<Void> andThen(Try.CheckedRunnable runnable)
        Runs the given runnable if this is a Success, otherwise returns this Failure. Shorthand for flatMap(ignored -> Try.run(runnable)). The main use case is chaining runnables using method references: 
         
 Try.run(A::methodRef).andThen(B::methodRef).andThen(C::methodRef);
        Please note that these lines are semantically the same: 
         
 Try.run(() -> { doStuff(); })
    .andThen(() -> { doMoreStuff(); })
    .andThen(() -> { doEvenMoreStuff(); });

 Try.run(() -> {
     doStuff();
     doMoreStuff();
     doEvenMoreStuff();
 });
        Parameters:
        runnable - A checked runnable
        Returns:
        a new Try
